{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_5a5835e8be8848aaab2a087f","type":"tool_result","content":"1\tgiskard-checks\n2\t===============\n3\t\n4\tLightweight primitives to define and run checks against model interactions.\n5\t\n6\tThis library provides:\n7\t\n8\t- Core types for describing interactions (`Interact`, `Interaction`, `Trace`)\n9\t- A fluent scenario builder and runner (`Scenario`, `ScenarioResult`)\n10\t- Built-in checks including string matching, comparisons, and LLM-based evaluation\n11\t- JSONPath-based extraction utilities for referencing trace data\n12\t- Seamless integration with `giskard-agents` generators for LLM-backed checks\n13\t\n14\tInstallation\n15\t------------\n16\t\n17\t```bash\n18\tpip install giskard-checks\n19\t```\n20\t\n21\tRequires Python >= 3.12.\n22\t\n23\t**Dependencies:**\n24\t- `pydantic>=2.11.7` - Core data validation and serialization\n25\t- `giskard-agents>=0.3` - LLM integration and workflow management\n26\t- `jsonpath-ng>=1.7.0` - JSONPath expressions for data extraction\n27\t- `jinja2>=3.1.6` - Template engine for LLM prompts\n28\t\n29\tQuickstart\n30\t----------\n31\t\n32\tUse the fluent API to create and run scenarios:\n33\t\n34\t```python\n35\tfrom giskard.checks import Groundedness, Scenario\n36\t\n37\t# Natural variable name: no shadowing (Scenario is the class, scenario is your instance)\n38\tscenario = (\n39\t    Scenario(\"test_france_capital\")\n40\t    .interact(\n41\t        inputs=\"What is the capital of France?\",\n42\t        outputs=\"The capital of France is Paris.\"\n43\t    )\n44\t    .check(\n45\t        Groundedness(\n46\t            name=\"answer is grounded\",\n47\t            answer_key=\"trace.last.outputs\",\n48\t            context=\"\"\"France is a country in Western Europe. Its capital\n49\t                       and largest city is Paris, known for the Eiffel Tower\n50\t                       and the Louvre Museum.\"\"\"\n51\t        )\n52\t    )\n53\t)\n54\t\n55\tresult = await scenario.run()\n56\tassert result.passed\n57\tprint(f\"Scenario completed in {result.duration_ms}ms\")\n58\t```\n59\t\n60\tThe fluent API accepts static values or callables for `inputs` and `outputs`, so you can call your SUT directly:\n61\t\n62\t```python\n63\tfrom openai import OpenAI\n64\tfrom giskard.checks import Groundedness, Scenario\n65\t\n66\tclient = OpenAI()\n67\t\n68\tdef get_answer(inputs: str) -> str:\n69\t    response = client.chat.completions.create(\n70\t        model=\"gpt-5-mini\",\n71\t        messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": inputs}],\n72\t    )\n73\t    return response.choices[0].message.content\n74\t\n75\tscenario = (\n76\t    Scenario(\"test_dynamic_output\")\n77\t    .interact(\n78\t        inputs=\"What is the capital of France?\",\n79\t        outputs=get_answer\n80\t    )\n81\t    .check(\n82\t        Groundedness(\n83\t            name=\"answer is grounded\",\n84\t            answer_key=\"trace.last.outputs\",\n85\t            context=\"France is a country in Western Europe...\"\n86\t        )\n87\t    )\n88\t)\n89\t```\n90\t\n91\tThe `run()` method is async. In a script, wrap it with `asyncio.run()`:\n92\t\n93\t```python\n94\timport asyncio\n95\t\n96\tasync def main():\n97\t    result = await scenario.run()\n98\t    print(result)\n99\t\n100\tasyncio.run(main())\n101\t```\n102\t\n103\tRunning Multiple Scenarios with Suite\n104\t-------------------------------------\n105\t\n106\tUse a `Suite` to run multiple scenarios against a shared target SUT. You can bind a target at the suite level or override it during the `run()` call.\n107\t\n108\t```python\n109\tfrom giskard.checks import Equals, Scenario, Suite\n110\t\n111\t# Define some scenarios without a target (no shadowing: Scenario is the class)\n112\tscenario1 = (\n113\t    Scenario(\"s1\")\n114\t    .interact(\"hello\")\n115\t    .check(Equals(expected_value=\"Echo: hello\", key=\"trace.last.outputs\"))\n116\t)\n117\tscenario2 = (\n118\t    Scenario(\"s2\")\n119\t    .interact(\"world\")\n120\t    .check(Equals(expected_value=\"Echo: world\", key=\"trace.last.outputs\"))\n121\t)\n122\t\n123\t# Create a suite with a shared target\n124\ttarget_sut = lambda inputs: f\"Echo: {inputs}\"\n125\tsuite = Suite(name=\"my_suite\", target=target_sut)\n126\t\n127\t# Add scenarios\n128\tsuite.append(scenario1)\n129\tsuite.append(scenario2)\n130\t\n131\t# Run the suite\n132\tresults = await suite.run()\n133\tprint(f\"Aggregated pass rate: {results.pass_rate * 100}%\")\n134\t```\n135\t\n136\tWhy this library?\n137\t-----------------\n138\t\n139\t- Small, explicit, and type-safe with `pydantic` models\n140\t- Async-friendly: checks can be sync or async\n141\t- Results are immutable and easy to serialize\n142\t\n143\tConcepts\n144\t--------\n145\t\n146\t- **Fluent API**: The recommended way to create tests using `Scenario(...).interact().check()`. This API builds a scenario and handles interaction generation.\n147\t- **Interact**: A specification for generating interactions dynamically (static values, callables, or generators).\n148\t- **Trace**: Immutable history of all `Interaction` objects produced while executing a scenario. Use `trace.last` in JSONPath expressions (e.g., `trace.last.outputs`).\n149\t- **Interaction**: A recorded exchange with `inputs`, `outputs`, and optional `metadata`.\n150\t- **Check**: Inspects the `Trace` and returns a `CheckResult`.\n151\t- **Scenario**: Ordered sequence of interactions and checks with a shared `Trace`. Execution stops at the first failing check and later steps are skipped. Scenarios can have their own `target` SUT, which will be injected to interactions without defined outputs.\n152\t- **Suite**: A collection of scenarios that can be executed together, optionally sharing a common `target`.\n153\t\n154\t**Advanced concepts** (used internally by the fluent API):\n155\t- **TestCase**: Wrapper that runs a set of checks against a single trace step and returns a `TestCaseResult`.\n156\t- **ScenarioRunner**: Executes scenarios sequentially, maintaining trace state and aggregating step results.\n157\t\n158\tAPI Overview\n159\t------------\n160\t\n161\t**Core types**\n162\t- `giskard.checks.Check`: base class for all checks with discriminated-union registration.\n163\t- `giskard.checks.CheckResult`, `CheckStatus`, `Metric`: typed results with convenience helpers.\n164\t- `giskard.checks.Trace` / `Interaction`: a trace is an immutable sequence of recorded interactions with the system.\n165\t- `giskard.checks.Scenario` and `ScenarioResult`: ordered sequence of components with shared trace. Execution stops at first failure and later steps are skipped.\n166\t- `giskard.checks.TestCase` and `TestCaseResult`: runs checks against a trace step and aggregates results.\n167\t\n168\t**Interaction specs**\n169\t- `giskard.checks.InteractionSpec`: discriminated base for describing inputs/outputs. Subclasses implement `generate()` to yield interactions.\n170\t- `giskard.checks.Interact`: batteries-included spec that supports static values, callables, generators, or `InputGenerator` instances for both inputs and outputs. Supports multi-turn interactions via generators.\n171\t- `giskard.checks.UserSimulator`: LLM-powered input generator that simulates user personas (predefined or custom) for multi-turn scenarios.\n172\t\n173\t**Scenarios and runners**\n174\t- `giskard.checks.Scenario`: ordered sequence of components (InteractionSpecs and Checks) with shared trace. Components execute sequentially, stopping at first failure.\n175\t- `giskard.checks.ScenarioRunner`: executes scenarios with timing, error capture, and early-stop semantics.\n176\t- `giskard.checks.TestCaseRunner`: executes test cases with timing and error handling.\n177\t\n178\t**Built-in and LLM-based checks**\n179\t- `giskard.checks.from_fn`, `FnCheck`: wrap arbitrary callables.\n180\t- `giskard.checks.StringMatching`, `RegexMatching`, `SemanticSimilarity`, `Equals`, `NotEquals`, `GreaterThan`, `GreaterEquals`, `LesserThan`, `LesserThanEquals`.\n181\t- `giskard.checks.BaseLLMCheck`, `LLMCheckResult`, `Groundedness`, `Conformity`, `LLMJudge`.\n182\t- JSONPath selectors (e.g., `trace.last.outputs`) are supported on relevant checks via `key` or check-specific fields like `answer_key`.\n183\t\n184\t**Testing utilities**\n185\t- `giskard.checks.WithSpy`: wrapper for spying on function calls during interaction generation.\n186\t\n187\t**Settings**\n188\t- `giskard.checks.set_default_generator` / `get_default_generator`: configure the generator used by LLM checks.\n189\t\n190\tTesting\n191\t-------\n192\t\n193\t- Tests live under `tests/` mirroring the package structure (`tests/core`, `tests/scenarios`, `tests/trace`).\n194\t- Use `make test` (or `make ci`) to run the full suite exactly as CI does.\n195\t\n196\tUsage Notes\n197\t-----------\n198\t\n199\t- Define custom checks with a unique `KIND` via `@Check.register(\"kind\")`.\n200\t- All discriminated types auto-register when imported; ensure modules are imported before deserialization.\n201\t- Prefer `model_dump()` / `model_validate()` for serialization.\n202\t- Attach extra metadata in `CheckResult.details`; JSONPath helpers (`key=...`) resolve against the entire trace.\n203\t\n204\tSerialization\n205\t-------------\n206\t\n207\tThe library uses Pydantic's discriminated unions for polymorphic serialization.\n208\t\n209\t```python\n210\tfrom giskard.checks import Check, CheckResult, Interaction, TestCase, Trace\n211\t\n212\t\n213\t@Check.register(\"my_custom_check\")\n214\tclass MyCustomCheck(Check):\n215\t    async def run(self, trace: Trace) -> CheckResult:\n216\t        return CheckResult.success(\"Check passed\")\n217\t\n218\t\n219\ttrace = Trace(interactions=[Interaction(inputs=\"test\", outputs=\"result\")])\n220\tcheck = MyCustomCheck(name=\"test\")\n221\ttestcase = TestCase(trace=trace, checks=[check], name=\"example\")\n222\t\n223\t# Serialize to dict\n224\tserialized = testcase.model_dump()\n225\t\n226\t# Deserialize back (requires classes to be imported)\n227\trestored = TestCase.model_validate(serialized)\n228\t```\n229\t\n230\t**Important**: Import every custom type (checks and specs) before calling `model_validate()`. The registry only knows about classes already loaded into memory.\n231\t\n232\tCreating Custom Checks and Interaction Specs\n233\t--------------------------------------------\n234\t\n235\t### Step 1: Define a custom check\n236\t\n237\t```python\n238\tfrom giskard.checks import Check, CheckResult, Trace\n239\t\n240\t\n241\t@Check.register(\"advanced_security\")\n242\tclass AdvancedSecurityCheck(Check):\n243\t    threshold: float = 0.8\n244\t\n245\t    async def run(self, trace: Trace) -> CheckResult:\n246\t        current = trace.last\n247\t        score = await some_security_analysis(current.outputs)\n248\t        if score >= self.threshold:\n249\t            return CheckResult.success(f\"Security score {score:.2f} meets threshold\")\n250\t        return CheckResult.failure(\n251\t            f\"Security score {score:.2f} below threshold {self.threshold}\"\n252\t        )\n253\t```\n254\t\n255\t### Step 2: Define a custom interaction specification\n256\t\n257\t```python\n258\tfrom giskard.checks import InteractionSpec, Interaction, Trace\n259\t\n260\t\n261\t@InteractionSpec.register(\"chat_conversation\")\n262\tclass ChatInteraction(InteractionSpec):\n263\t    session_id: str\n264\t    messages: list[str]\n265\t\n266\t    async def generate(self, trace: Trace):\n267\t        summary = f\"Conversation with {len(self.messages)} messages\"\n268\t        record = Interaction(\n269\t            inputs=self.messages,\n270\t            outputs={\"summary\": summary},\n271\t            metadata={\"session_id\": self.session_id},\n272\t        )\n273\t        yield record\n274\t```\n275\t\n276\t### Step 3: Verify registration\n277\t\n278\t```python\n279\tfrom giskard.checks import Scenario\n280\t\n281\tchat = ChatInteraction(session_id=\"session_123\", messages=[\"hi\", \"hello\"])\n282\tcheck = AdvancedSecurityCheck(name=\"security_test\", threshold=0.7)\n283\tscenario = Scenario(name=\"custom_test\").extend(chat, check)\n284\t\n285\tserialized = scenario.model_dump()\n286\trestored = Scenario.model_validate(serialized)\n287\t```\n288\t\n289\t### Binding a Target SUT\n290\t\n291\tYou can bind a System Under Test (SUT) at three different levels, with the following precedence:\n292\t`run(target=...)` > `Suite(target=...)` > `Scenario(..., target=...)`.\n293\t\n294\t#### 1. Scenario Level\n295\tPass the target directly to `Scenario()`:\n296\t```python\n297\tresult = await Scenario(\"test\", target=my_sut).interact(\"hello\").run()\n298\t```\n299\t\n300\t#### 2. Suite Level\n301\tBind a target to all scenarios in a suite:\n302\t```python\n303\tsuite = Suite(name=\"my_suite\", target=shared_sut)\n304\tsuite.append(scenario)\n305\tresult = await suite.run()\n306\t```\n307\t\n308\t#### 3. Run Level\n309\tOverride everything at execution time:\n310\t```python\n311\t# This target will be used for all scenarios in the suite,\n312\t# overriding any suite-level or scenario-level targets.\n313\tresult = await suite.run(target=emergency_override_sut)\n314\t```\n315\t\n316\tTroubleshooting Serialization Issues\n317\t------------------------------------\n318\t\n319\t**ValidationError**: \"Kind is not provided for Check\"\n320\t- Cause: Custom class not imported before deserialization.\n321\t- Fix: Import classes before calling `model_validate()`.\n322\t\n323\t**DuplicateKindError**: \"Duplicate kind 'my_check' detected\"\n324\t- Cause: Two classes share the same `KIND`.\n325\t- Fix: Give every registered class a unique `KIND`.\n326\t\n327\t**Missing registration**\n328\t- Cause: Subclass missing the decorator.\n329\t- Fix: Use `@Check.register(\"...\")` (or the relevant base).\n330\t\n331\t**Import order issues in tests**\n332\t- Cause: Tests call `model_validate()` before importing custom modules.\n333\t- Fix: Import those modules in test setup or fixtures first.\n334\t\n335\tStructured data example\n336\t------------------------\n337\t\n338\t```python\n339\tfrom giskard.checks import Equals, Scenario, StringMatching\n340\t\n341\tresult = await (\n342\t    Scenario(\"structured-example\")\n343\t    .interact(\n344\t        {\"question\": \"What is the capital of France?\"},\n345\t        lambda inputs: {\"answer\": \"Paris is the capital of France.\", \"confidence\": 0.95}\n346\t    )\n347\t    .check(StringMatching(\n348\t        name=\"contains_paris\",\n349\t        keyword=\"Paris\",\n350\t        text_key=\"trace.last.outputs.answer\",\n351\t    ))\n352\t    .check(Equals(\n353\t        name=\"high_confidence\",\n354\t        expected_value=0.95,\n355\t        key=\"trace.last.outputs.confidence\",\n356\t    ))\n357\t    .run()\n358\t)\n359\t\n360\tassert result.passed\n361\tprint(f\"Scenario completed in {result.duration_ms}ms\")\n362\t```\n363\t\n364\tMulti-step workflows\n365\t---------------------\n366\t\n367\tUse the fluent API to create multi-turn scenarios. Components execute sequentially with a shared trace, stopping at the first failing check.\n368\t\n369\t```python\n370\tfrom giskard.checks import LLMJudge, RegexMatching, Scenario\n371\t\n372\tresult = await (\n373\t    Scenario(\"multi_step_conversation\")\n374\t    .interact(\n375\t        \"Hello, I want to apply for a job.\",\n376\t        lambda inputs: \"Hi! I'd be happy to help. Please provide your email.\"\n377\t    )\n378\t    .check(LLMJudge(\n379\t        prompt=\"The assistant asked for the email politely: {{ trace.last.outputs }}\"\n380\t    ))\n381\t    .interact(\n382\t        \"My email is test@example.com\",\n383\t        lambda inputs: f\"Thank you! I've saved your application with email: {inputs.split()[-1]}\"\n384\t    )\n385\t    .check(RegexMatching(\n386\t        pattern=\"test@example.com\",\n387\t        text_key=\"trace.last.outputs\",\n388\t    ))\n389\t    .run()\n390\t)\n391\t\n392\tassert result.passed\n393\t```\n394\t\n395\tDynamic interaction generation\n396\t------------------------------\n397\t\n398\tThe fluent API supports callables (sync/async) or generators for dynamic inputs. Multiple inputs can be produced by yielding from a generator.\n399\t\n400\t```python\n401\tfrom giskard.checks import Scenario, Trace, from_fn\n402\t\n403\t\n404\tasync def input_generator(trace: Trace):\n405\t    count = len(trace.interactions)\n406\t    next_input = {\"message\": f\"Hello! This is message #{count + 1}\"}\n407\t    yield next_input  # Can also yield multiple times for streaming inputs\n408\t\n409\t\n410\tresult = await (\n411\t    Scenario(\"dynamic-example\")\n412\t    .interact(\n413\t        input_generator,\n414\t        lambda inputs: {\n415\t            \"response\": f\"Hi there! Received: {inputs['message']}\",\n416\t        }\n417\t    )\n418\t    .check(from_fn(lambda trace: True, name=\"noop\"))\n419\t    .run()\n420\t)\n421\t```\n422\t\n423\tUser simulation\n424\t--------------\n425\t\n426\tUse `UserSimulator` for LLM-powered user personas in multi-turn scenarios. Supports predefined personas (e.g., ``frustrated_customer``, ``helpful_user``) or custom descriptions.\n427\t\n428\t```python\n429\tfrom giskard.checks import scenario, UserSimulator, set_default_generator\n430\tfrom giskard.agents.generators import Generator\n431\t\n432\tset_default_generator(Generator(model=\"openai/gpt-4o-mini\"))\n433\t\n434\tresult = await (\n435\t    scenario(\"user-simulation\")\n436\t    .interact(\n437\t        UserSimulator(persona=\"frustrated_customer\", context=\"delayed order\"),\n438\t        lambda inputs: \"I apologize for the delay. Let me look into that.\",\n439\t    )\n440\t    .run()\n441\t)\n442\t```\n443\t\n444\tLLM-based checks\n445\t----------------\n446\t\n447\t```python\n448\tfrom giskard.agents.generators import Generator\n449\t\n450\tfrom giskard.checks import (\n451\t    Conformity,\n452\t    LLMJudge,\n453\t    Scenario,\n454\t    set_default_generator,\n455\t)\n456\t\n457\t# Configure the default LLM generator\n458\tset_default_generator(Generator(model=\"openai/gpt-4o-mini\"))\n459\t\n460\tresult = await (\n461\t    Scenario(\"llm-example\")\n462\t    .interact(\n463\t        {\"question\": \"What is the capital of France?\"},\n464\t        lambda inputs: {\"answer\": \"Paris is the capital of France.\"}\n465\t    )\n466\t    .check(Conformity(name=\"conformity_check\", rule=\"The agent must answer in English\"))\n467\t    .check(LLMJudge(\n468\t        name=\"safety_check\",\n469\t        prompt=\"\"\"Evaluate if the following response is safe and appropriate.\n470\t\n471\tInput: {{ trace.last.inputs }}\n472\tResponse: {{ trace.last.outputs }}\n473\t\n474\tReturn 'passed: true' if safe, 'passed: false' if unsafe.\"\"\",\n475\t    ))\n476\t    .run()\n477\t)\n478\t\n479\tassert result.passed\n480\tprint(f\"LLM evaluation completed in {result.duration_ms}ms\")\n481\t```\n482\t\n483\tTemplate customization & advanced LLM usage\n484\t-------------------------------------------\n485\t\n486\t- LLM-based checks ship with template references registered inside `giskard.agents`.\n487\t- Provide your own template by overriding `get_prompt()` in a subclass or by instantiating `LLMJudge` with inline prompts.\n488\t- Templates use the same interpolation context you return from `get_inputs()`.\n489\t\n490\t```python\n491\tfrom giskard.agents.workflow import TemplateReference\n492\tfrom pydantic import BaseModel\n493\t\n494\tfrom giskard.checks import BaseLLMCheck, Check, CheckResult, Trace\n495\t\n496\t\n497\tclass CustomResult(BaseModel):\n498\t    score: float\n499\t    passed: bool\n500\t    reasoning: str\n501\t\n502\t\n503\t@Check.register(\"custom_llm_check\")\n504\tclass CustomLLMCheck(BaseLLMCheck):\n505\t    def get_prompt(self) -> TemplateReference:\n506\t        return TemplateReference(template_name=\"my_project::checks/custom_check.j2\")\n507\t\n508\t    @property\n509\t    def output_type(self) -> type[BaseModel]:\n510\t        return CustomResult\n511\t\n512\t    async def _handle_output(\n513\t        self,\n514\t        output_value: CustomResult,\n515\t        template_inputs: dict[str, str],\n516\t        trace: Trace,\n517\t    ) -> CheckResult:\n518\t        if output_value.score >= 0.8:\n519\t            return CheckResult.success(f\"Score {output_value.score} meets threshold\")\n520\t        return CheckResult.failure(f\"Score {output_value.score} below threshold\")\n521\t```\n522\t\n523\tNotes\n524\t-----\n525\t\n526\t- `Trace` captures every interaction; JSONPath keys like `trace.last.outputs` resolve against that structure.\n527\t- Pass a `generator` to individual LLM checks or rely on the default configured via `set_default_generator()`.\n528\t- Built-in LLM checks rely on templates bundled in `giskard.checks` and registered with the `giskard-agents` template system; override `get_prompt` or `get_inputs` for customization.\n529\t\n530\tAdvanced Usage\n531\t--------------\n532\t\n533\tFor advanced use cases where you need direct control over interactions or trace construction, you can build a `Trace` for `TestCase` directly, using `Interaction`:\n534\t\n535\t``` python\n536\tfrom giskard.checks import Interaction, TestCase, Trace\n537\t\n538\t# Build a Trace manually for a TestCase\n539\ttrace = Trace(interactions=[\n540\t    Interaction(inputs=\"some text\", outputs=process(\"some text\")),\n541\t])\n542\ttc = TestCase(trace=trace, checks=[check1, check2], name=\"advanced_example\")\n543\ttest_case_result = await tc.run()\n544\t```\n545\t\n546\tFor programmatic test generation or when you need fine-grained control, you can also construct `Scenario` objects directly, creating a sequence of `InteractionSpec` or `Check` objects:\n547\t\n548\t```python\n549\tfrom giskard.checks import (\n550\t    Scenario,\n551\t    Interact, # Inherits from `InteractionSpec`\n552\t    Equals # Inherits from `Check`\n553\t)\n554\t\n555\tscenario = Scenario(name=\"programmatic_scenario\").extend(\n556\t    Interact(inputs=\"Hello\", outputs=lambda inputs: \"Hi\"),\n557\t    Equals(expected_value=\"Hi\", key=\"trace.last.outputs\"),\n558\t)\n559\t\n560\tresult = await scenario.run()\n561\t```\n562\t\n563\t**Note**: For most use cases, the fluent API (`Scenario(...).interact().check()`) is recommended as it's simpler and more readable.\n564\t\n565\tDevelopment\n566\t-----------\n567\t\n568\tUse the Makefile for all development workflows (`make help` for details).\n569\t\n570\t```bash\n571\tmake install   # Install dependencies\n572\tmake setup     # Install dependencies + tools (Format, lint, typecheck, test)\n573\t```\n574\t\n575\tOther common commands:\n576\t\n577\t```bash\n578\tmake test\n579\tmake lint\n580\tmake format\n581\tmake typecheck\n582\tmake check\n583\tmake clean\n584\t```\n585\t\n586\tFor more details, see the [Makefile](Makefile) or run `make help`.\n587\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"cecb49f1-a503-4314-99a9-a51144ba81d8","uuid":"833bb22a-d078-4f1e-b8b6-dd9700230cbe","timestamp":"2026-04-06T17:30:41.790Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/libs/giskard-checks/README.md","content":"giskard-checks\n===============\n\nLightweight primitives to define and run checks against model interactions.\n\nThis library provides:\n\n- Core types for describing interactions (`Interact`, `Interaction`, `Trace`)\n- A fluent scenario builder and runner (`Scenario`, `ScenarioResult`)\n- Built-in checks including string matching, comparisons, and LLM-based evaluation\n- JSONPath-based extraction utilities for referencing trace data\n- Seamless integration with `giskard-agents` generators for LLM-backed checks\n\nInstallation\n------------\n\n```bash\npip install giskard-checks\n```\n\nRequires Python >= 3.12.\n\n**Dependencies:**\n- `pydantic>=2.11.7` - Core data validation and serialization\n- `giskard-agents>=0.3` - LLM integration and workflow management\n- `jsonpath-ng>=1.7.0` - JSONPath expressions for data extraction\n- `jinja2>=3.1.6` - Template engine for LLM prompts\n\nQuickstart\n----------\n\nUse the fluent API to create and run scenarios:\n\n```python\nfrom giskard.checks import Groundedness, Scenario\n\n# Natural variable name: no shadowing (Scenario is the class, scenario is your instance)\nscenario = (\n    Scenario(\"test_france_capital\")\n    .interact(\n        inputs=\"What is the capital of France?\",\n        outputs=\"The capital of France is Paris.\"\n    )\n    .check(\n        Groundedness(\n            name=\"answer is grounded\",\n            answer_key=\"trace.last.outputs\",\n            context=\"\"\"France is a country in Western Europe. Its capital\n                       and largest city is Paris, known for the Eiffel Tower\n                       and the Louvre Museum.\"\"\"\n        )\n    )\n)\n\nresult = await scenario.run()\nassert result.passed\nprint(f\"Scenario completed in {result.duration_ms}ms\")\n```\n\nThe fluent API accepts static values or callables for `inputs` and `outputs`, so you can call your SUT directly:\n\n```python\nfrom openai import OpenAI\nfrom giskard.checks import Groundedness, Scenario\n\nclient = OpenAI()\n\ndef get_answer(inputs: str) -> str:\n    response = client.chat.completions.create(\n        model=\"gpt-5-mini\",\n        messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": inputs}],\n    )\n    return response.choices[0].message.content\n\nscenario = (\n    Scenario(\"test_dynamic_output\")\n    .interact(\n        inputs=\"What is the capital of France?\",\n        outputs=get_answer\n    )\n    .check(\n        Groundedness(\n            name=\"answer is grounded\",\n            answer_key=\"trace.last.outputs\",\n            context=\"France is a country in Western Europe...\"\n        )\n    )\n)\n```\n\nThe `run()` method is async. In a script, wrap it with `asyncio.run()`:\n\n```python\nimport asyncio\n\nasync def main():\n    result = await scenario.run()\n    print(result)\n\nasyncio.run(main())\n```\n\nRunning Multiple Scenarios with Suite\n-------------------------------------\n\nUse a `Suite` to run multiple scenarios against a shared target SUT. You can bind a target at the suite level or override it during the `run()` call.\n\n```python\nfrom giskard.checks import Equals, Scenario, Suite\n\n# Define some scenarios without a target (no shadowing: Scenario is the class)\nscenario1 = (\n    Scenario(\"s1\")\n    .interact(\"hello\")\n    .check(Equals(expected_value=\"Echo: hello\", key=\"trace.last.outputs\"))\n)\nscenario2 = (\n    Scenario(\"s2\")\n    .interact(\"world\")\n    .check(Equals(expected_value=\"Echo: world\", key=\"trace.last.outputs\"))\n)\n\n# Create a suite with a shared target\ntarget_sut = lambda inputs: f\"Echo: {inputs}\"\nsuite = Suite(name=\"my_suite\", target=target_sut)\n\n# Add scenarios\nsuite.append(scenario1)\nsuite.append(scenario2)\n\n# Run the suite\nresults = await suite.run()\nprint(f\"Aggregated pass rate: {results.pass_rate * 100}%\")\n```\n\nWhy this library?\n-----------------\n\n- Small, explicit, and type-safe with `pydantic` models\n- Async-friendly: checks can be sync or async\n- Results are immutable and easy to serialize\n\nConcepts\n--------\n\n- **Fluent API**: The recommended way to create tests using `Scenario(...).interact().check()`. This API builds a scenario and handles interaction generation.\n- **Interact**: A specification for generating interactions dynamically (static values, callables, or generators).\n- **Trace**: Immutable history of all `Interaction` objects produced while executing a scenario. Use `trace.last` in JSONPath expressions (e.g., `trace.last.outputs`).\n- **Interaction**: A recorded exchange with `inputs`, `outputs`, and optional `metadata`.\n- **Check**: Inspects the `Trace` and returns a `CheckResult`.\n- **Scenario**: Ordered sequence of interactions and checks with a shared `Trace`. Execution stops at the first failing check and later steps are skipped. Scenarios can have their own `target` SUT, which will be injected to interactions without defined outputs.\n- **Suite**: A collection of scenarios that can be executed together, optionally sharing a common `target`.\n\n**Advanced concepts** (used internally by the fluent API):\n- **TestCase**: Wrapper that runs a set of checks against a single trace step and returns a `TestCaseResult`.\n- **ScenarioRunner**: Executes scenarios sequentially, maintaining trace state and aggregating step results.\n\nAPI Overview\n------------\n\n**Core types**\n- `giskard.checks.Check`: base class for all checks with discriminated-union registration.\n- `giskard.checks.CheckResult`, `CheckStatus`, `Metric`: typed results with convenience helpers.\n- `giskard.checks.Trace` / `Interaction`: a trace is an immutable sequence of recorded interactions with the system.\n- `giskard.checks.Scenario` and `ScenarioResult`: ordered sequence of components with shared trace. Execution stops at first failure and later steps are skipped.\n- `giskard.checks.TestCase` and `TestCaseResult`: runs checks against a trace step and aggregates results.\n\n**Interaction specs**\n- `giskard.checks.InteractionSpec`: discriminated base for describing inputs/outputs. Subclasses implement `generate()` to yield interactions.\n- `giskard.checks.Interact`: batteries-included spec that supports static values, callables, generators, or `InputGenerator` instances for both inputs and outputs. Supports multi-turn interactions via generators.\n- `giskard.checks.UserSimulator`: LLM-powered input generator that simulates user personas (predefined or custom) for multi-turn scenarios.\n\n**Scenarios and runners**\n- `giskard.checks.Scenario`: ordered sequence of components (InteractionSpecs and Checks) with shared trace. Components execute sequentially, stopping at first failure.\n- `giskard.checks.ScenarioRunner`: executes scenarios with timing, error capture, and early-stop semantics.\n- `giskard.checks.TestCaseRunner`: executes test cases with timing and error handling.\n\n**Built-in and LLM-based checks**\n- `giskard.checks.from_fn`, `FnCheck`: wrap arbitrary callables.\n- `giskard.checks.StringMatching`, `RegexMatching`, `SemanticSimilarity`, `Equals`, `NotEquals`, `GreaterThan`, `GreaterEquals`, `LesserThan`, `LesserThanEquals`.\n- `giskard.checks.BaseLLMCheck`, `LLMCheckResult`, `Groundedness`, `Conformity`, `LLMJudge`.\n- JSONPath selectors (e.g., `trace.last.outputs`) are supported on relevant checks via `key` or check-specific fields like `answer_key`.\n\n**Testing utilities**\n- `giskard.checks.WithSpy`: wrapper for spying on function calls during interaction generation.\n\n**Settings**\n- `giskard.checks.set_default_generator` / `get_default_generator`: configure the generator used by LLM checks.\n\nTesting\n-------\n\n- Tests live under `tests/` mirroring the package structure (`tests/core`, `tests/scenarios`, `tests/trace`).\n- Use `make test` (or `make ci`) to run the full suite exactly as CI does.\n\nUsage Notes\n-----------\n\n- Define custom checks with a unique `KIND` via `@Check.register(\"kind\")`.\n- All discriminated types auto-register when imported; ensure modules are imported before deserialization.\n- Prefer `model_dump()` / `model_validate()` for serialization.\n- Attach extra metadata in `CheckResult.details`; JSONPath helpers (`key=...`) resolve against the entire trace.\n\nSerialization\n-------------\n\nThe library uses Pydantic's discriminated unions for polymorphic serialization.\n\n```python\nfrom giskard.checks import Check, CheckResult, Interaction, TestCase, Trace\n\n\n@Check.register(\"my_custom_check\")\nclass MyCustomCheck(Check):\n    async def run(self, trace: Trace) -> CheckResult:\n        return CheckResult.success(\"Check passed\")\n\n\ntrace = Trace(interactions=[Interaction(inputs=\"test\", outputs=\"result\")])\ncheck = MyCustomCheck(name=\"test\")\ntestcase = TestCase(trace=trace, checks=[check], name=\"example\")\n\n# Serialize to dict\nserialized = testcase.model_dump()\n\n# Deserialize back (requires classes to be imported)\nrestored = TestCase.model_validate(serialized)\n```\n\n**Important**: Import every custom type (checks and specs) before calling `model_validate()`. The registry only knows about classes already loaded into memory.\n\nCreating Custom Checks and Interaction Specs\n--------------------------------------------\n\n### Step 1: Define a custom check\n\n```python\nfrom giskard.checks import Check, CheckResult, Trace\n\n\n@Check.register(\"advanced_security\")\nclass AdvancedSecurityCheck(Check):\n    threshold: float = 0.8\n\n    async def run(self, trace: Trace) -> CheckResult:\n        current = trace.last\n        score = await some_security_analysis(current.outputs)\n        if score >= self.threshold:\n            return CheckResult.success(f\"Security score {score:.2f} meets threshold\")\n        return CheckResult.failure(\n            f\"Security score {score:.2f} below threshold {self.threshold}\"\n        )\n```\n\n### Step 2: Define a custom interaction specification\n\n```python\nfrom giskard.checks import InteractionSpec, Interaction, Trace\n\n\n@InteractionSpec.register(\"chat_conversation\")\nclass ChatInteraction(InteractionSpec):\n    session_id: str\n    messages: list[str]\n\n    async def generate(self, trace: Trace):\n        summary = f\"Conversation with {len(self.messages)} messages\"\n        record = Interaction(\n            inputs=self.messages,\n            outputs={\"summary\": summary},\n            metadata={\"session_id\": self.session_id},\n        )\n        yield record\n```\n\n### Step 3: Verify registration\n\n```python\nfrom giskard.checks import Scenario\n\nchat = ChatInteraction(session_id=\"session_123\", messages=[\"hi\", \"hello\"])\ncheck = AdvancedSecurityCheck(name=\"security_test\", threshold=0.7)\nscenario = Scenario(name=\"custom_test\").extend(chat, check)\n\nserialized = scenario.model_dump()\nrestored = Scenario.model_validate(serialized)\n```\n\n### Binding a Target SUT\n\nYou can bind a System Under Test (SUT) at three different levels, with the following precedence:\n`run(target=...)` > `Suite(target=...)` > `Scenario(..., target=...)`.\n\n#### 1. Scenario Level\nPass the target directly to `Scenario()`:\n```python\nresult = await Scenario(\"test\", target=my_sut).interact(\"hello\").run()\n```\n\n#### 2. Suite Level\nBind a target to all scenarios in a suite:\n```python\nsuite = Suite(name=\"my_suite\", target=shared_sut)\nsuite.append(scenario)\nresult = await suite.run()\n```\n\n#### 3. Run Level\nOverride everything at execution time:\n```python\n# This target will be used for all scenarios in the suite,\n# overriding any suite-level or scenario-level targets.\nresult = await suite.run(target=emergency_override_sut)\n```\n\nTroubleshooting Serialization Issues\n------------------------------------\n\n**ValidationError**: \"Kind is not provided for Check\"\n- Cause: Custom class not imported before deserialization.\n- Fix: Import classes before calling `model_validate()`.\n\n**DuplicateKindError**: \"Duplicate kind 'my_check' detected\"\n- Cause: Two classes share the same `KIND`.\n- Fix: Give every registered class a unique `KIND`.\n\n**Missing registration**\n- Cause: Subclass missing the decorator.\n- Fix: Use `@Check.register(\"...\")` (or the relevant base).\n\n**Import order issues in tests**\n- Cause: Tests call `model_validate()` before importing custom modules.\n- Fix: Import those modules in test setup or fixtures first.\n\nStructured data example\n------------------------\n\n```python\nfrom giskard.checks import Equals, Scenario, StringMatching\n\nresult = await (\n    Scenario(\"structured-example\")\n    .interact(\n        {\"question\": \"What is the capital of France?\"},\n        lambda inputs: {\"answer\": \"Paris is the capital of France.\", \"confidence\": 0.95}\n    )\n    .check(StringMatching(\n        name=\"contains_paris\",\n        keyword=\"Paris\",\n        text_key=\"trace.last.outputs.answer\",\n    ))\n    .check(Equals(\n        name=\"high_confidence\",\n        expected_value=0.95,\n        key=\"trace.last.outputs.confidence\",\n    ))\n    .run()\n)\n\nassert result.passed\nprint(f\"Scenario completed in {result.duration_ms}ms\")\n```\n\nMulti-step workflows\n---------------------\n\nUse the fluent API to create multi-turn scenarios. Components execute sequentially with a shared trace, stopping at the first failing check.\n\n```python\nfrom giskard.checks import LLMJudge, RegexMatching, Scenario\n\nresult = await (\n    Scenario(\"multi_step_conversation\")\n    .interact(\n        \"Hello, I want to apply for a job.\",\n        lambda inputs: \"Hi! I'd be happy to help. Please provide your email.\"\n    )\n    .check(LLMJudge(\n        prompt=\"The assistant asked for the email politely: {{ trace.last.outputs }}\"\n    ))\n    .interact(\n        \"My email is test@example.com\",\n        lambda inputs: f\"Thank you! I've saved your application with email: {inputs.split()[-1]}\"\n    )\n    .check(RegexMatching(\n        pattern=\"test@example.com\",\n        text_key=\"trace.last.outputs\",\n    ))\n    .run()\n)\n\nassert result.passed\n```\n\nDynamic interaction generation\n------------------------------\n\nThe fluent API supports callables (sync/async) or generators for dynamic inputs. Multiple inputs can be produced by yielding from a generator.\n\n```python\nfrom giskard.checks import Scenario, Trace, from_fn\n\n\nasync def input_generator(trace: Trace):\n    count = len(trace.interactions)\n    next_input = {\"message\": f\"Hello! This is message #{count + 1}\"}\n    yield next_input  # Can also yield multiple times for streaming inputs\n\n\nresult = await (\n    Scenario(\"dynamic-example\")\n    .interact(\n        input_generator,\n        lambda inputs: {\n            \"response\": f\"Hi there! Received: {inputs['message']}\",\n        }\n    )\n    .check(from_fn(lambda trace: True, name=\"noop\"))\n    .run()\n)\n```\n\nUser simulation\n--------------\n\nUse `UserSimulator` for LLM-powered user personas in multi-turn scenarios. Supports predefined personas (e.g., ``frustrated_customer``, ``helpful_user``) or custom descriptions.\n\n```python\nfrom giskard.checks import scenario, UserSimulator, set_default_generator\nfrom giskard.agents.generators import Generator\n\nset_default_generator(Generator(model=\"openai/gpt-4o-mini\"))\n\nresult = await (\n    scenario(\"user-simulation\")\n    .interact(\n        UserSimulator(persona=\"frustrated_customer\", context=\"delayed order\"),\n        lambda inputs: \"I apologize for the delay. Let me look into that.\",\n    )\n    .run()\n)\n```\n\nLLM-based checks\n----------------\n\n```python\nfrom giskard.agents.generators import Generator\n\nfrom giskard.checks import (\n    Conformity,\n    LLMJudge,\n    Scenario,\n    set_default_generator,\n)\n\n# Configure the default LLM generator\nset_default_generator(Generator(model=\"openai/gpt-4o-mini\"))\n\nresult = await (\n    Scenario(\"llm-example\")\n    .interact(\n        {\"question\": \"What is the capital of France?\"},\n        lambda inputs: {\"answer\": \"Paris is the capital of France.\"}\n    )\n    .check(Conformity(name=\"conformity_check\", rule=\"The agent must answer in English\"))\n    .check(LLMJudge(\n        name=\"safety_check\",\n        prompt=\"\"\"Evaluate if the following response is safe and appropriate.\n\nInput: {{ trace.last.inputs }}\nResponse: {{ trace.last.outputs }}\n\nReturn 'passed: true' if safe, 'passed: false' if unsafe.\"\"\",\n    ))\n    .run()\n)\n\nassert result.passed\nprint(f\"LLM evaluation completed in {result.duration_ms}ms\")\n```\n\nTemplate customization & advanced LLM usage\n-------------------------------------------\n\n- LLM-based checks ship with template references registered inside `giskard.agents`.\n- Provide your own template by overriding `get_prompt()` in a subclass or by instantiating `LLMJudge` with inline prompts.\n- Templates use the same interpolation context you return from `get_inputs()`.\n\n```python\nfrom giskard.agents.workflow import TemplateReference\nfrom pydantic import BaseModel\n\nfrom giskard.checks import BaseLLMCheck, Check, CheckResult, Trace\n\n\nclass CustomResult(BaseModel):\n    score: float\n    passed: bool\n    reasoning: str\n\n\n@Check.register(\"custom_llm_check\")\nclass CustomLLMCheck(BaseLLMCheck):\n    def get_prompt(self) -> TemplateReference:\n        return TemplateReference(template_name=\"my_project::checks/custom_check.j2\")\n\n    @property\n    def output_type(self) -> type[BaseModel]:\n        return CustomResult\n\n    async def _handle_output(\n        self,\n        output_value: CustomResult,\n        template_inputs: dict[str, str],\n        trace: Trace,\n    ) -> CheckResult:\n        if output_value.score >= 0.8:\n            return CheckResult.success(f\"Score {output_value.score} meets threshold\")\n        return CheckResult.failure(f\"Score {output_value.score} below threshold\")\n```\n\nNotes\n-----\n\n- `Trace` captures every interaction; JSONPath keys like `trace.last.outputs` resolve against that structure.\n- Pass a `generator` to individual LLM checks or rely on the default configured via `set_default_generator()`.\n- Built-in LLM checks rely on templates bundled in `giskard.checks` and registered with the `giskard-agents` template system; override `get_prompt` or `get_inputs` for customization.\n\nAdvanced Usage\n--------------\n\nFor advanced use cases where you need direct control over interactions or trace construction, you can build a `Trace` for `TestCase` directly, using `Interaction`:\n\n``` python\nfrom giskard.checks import Interaction, TestCase, Trace\n\n# Build a Trace manually for a TestCase\ntrace = Trace(interactions=[\n    Interaction(inputs=\"some text\", outputs=process(\"some text\")),\n])\ntc = TestCase(trace=trace, checks=[check1, check2], name=\"advanced_example\")\ntest_case_result = await tc.run()\n```\n\nFor programmatic test generation or when you need fine-grained control, you can also construct `Scenario` objects directly, creating a sequence of `InteractionSpec` or `Check` objects:\n\n```python\nfrom giskard.checks import (\n    Scenario,\n    Interact, # Inherits from `InteractionSpec`\n    Equals # Inherits from `Check`\n)\n\nscenario = Scenario(name=\"programmatic_scenario\").extend(\n    Interact(inputs=\"Hello\", outputs=lambda inputs: \"Hi\"),\n    Equals(expected_value=\"Hi\", key=\"trace.last.outputs\"),\n)\n\nresult = await scenario.run()\n```\n\n**Note**: For most use cases, the fluent API (`Scenario(...).interact().check()`) is recommended as it's simpler and more readable.\n\nDevelopment\n-----------\n\nUse the Makefile for all development workflows (`make help` for details).\n\n```bash\nmake install   # Install dependencies\nmake setup     # Install dependencies + tools (Format, lint, typecheck, test)\n```\n\nOther common commands:\n\n```bash\nmake test\nmake lint\nmake format\nmake typecheck\nmake check\nmake clean\n```\n\nFor more details, see the [Makefile](Makefile) or run `make help`.\n","numLines":587,"startLine":1,"totalLines":587}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_283e77e5a6704f9490b30b9d","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Giskard Agents\n2\t\n3\tGiskard Agents is a lightweight library that orchestrates LLM completions and agents in parallel workflows. It enables multiple AI workflows to run independently while maintaining coordination and synchronization between them.\n4\t\n5\t## Requirements\n6\t\n7\t- Python 3.12 or higher\n8\t\n9\t## Installation\n10\t\n11\t### Using uv (recommended)\n12\t\n13\tInstall the package:\n14\t\n15\t```bash\n16\tuv add giskard-agents\n17\t```\n18\t\n19\tFor development, install with dev dependencies:\n20\t\n21\t```bash\n22\tuv add giskard-agents --dev\n23\t```\n24\t\n25\t## Core Concepts\n26\t\n27\tThree basic elements to keep in mind:\n28\t\n29\t- `Generator` corresponds to a conversational text generator. It represents a model with certain params and can run completions.\n30\t- `ChatWorkflow` defines everything needed to run a chat with the generator. It handles templates, parsing, and tools.\n31\t- `Chat` is the result of a pipeline run. It contains the generated messages and metadata.\n32\t\n33\tThe API is async throughout — all run methods return coroutines.\n34\t\n35\t## Basic usage\n36\t\n37\t### Running a chat\n38\t\n39\t```python\n40\tfrom giskard import agents\n41\t\n42\tgenerator = agents.Generator(model=\"openai/gpt-4o-mini\")\n43\t\n44\t# generator.chat automatically creates a workflow that can be run.\n45\tchat = await generator.chat(\"Hello, how are you?\").run()\n46\t\n47\t# print the content of the last message (in this case, the assistant's response)\n48\tprint(chat.last.content)\n49\t```\n50\t\n51\tYou can run multiple chats in parallel:\n52\t\n53\t```python\n54\tchats = await generator.chat(\"Hello, how are you?\").run_many(n=3)\n55\t```\n56\t\n57\tOr add multiple messages to the workflow:\n58\t\n59\t```python\n60\t# The chat message role is \"user\" by default.\n61\tchat = await (\n62\t    generator\n63\t    .chat(\"You are a helpful assistant.\", role=\"system\")\n64\t    .chat(\"Hello, how are you?\")\n65\t    .chat(\"I'm fine, thank you!\", role=\"assistant\")\n66\t    .chat(\"What's your name?\")\n67\t    .run()\n68\t)\n69\t```\n70\t\n71\t## Retries and rate limiting\n72\t\n73\tGenerators have built-in support for retries and rate limiting via dedicated fields. The correct middleware ordering is handled automatically (retry wraps rate limiting wraps custom middlewares).\n74\t\n75\t### Retries\n76\t\n77\tBy default, `LiteLLMGenerator` retries failed requests with exponential backoff using LiteLLM's retry-eligibility logic. You can customize the retry policy:\n78\t\n79\t```python\n80\tfrom giskard.agents.generators.middleware import RetryPolicy\n81\t\n82\tgenerator = agents.Generator(\n83\t    model=\"openai/gpt-4o-mini\",\n84\t    retry_policy=RetryPolicy(max_attempts=5, base_delay=2.0, max_delay=30.0),\n85\t)\n86\t```\n87\t\n88\tOr use the convenience method:\n89\t\n90\t```python\n91\tgenerator = agents.Generator(model=\"openai/gpt-4o-mini\").with_retries(5, base_delay=2.0, max_delay=30.0)\n92\t```\n93\t\n94\t### Rate limiting\n95\t\n96\t```python\n97\tfrom giskard.core import MinIntervalRateLimiter\n98\t\n99\tgenerator = agents.Generator(\n100\t    model=\"openai/gpt-4o-mini\",\n101\t    rate_limiter=MinIntervalRateLimiter.from_rpm(60, max_concurrent=5),\n102\t)\n103\t```\n104\t\n105\tOr use the convenience method:\n106\t\n107\t```python\n108\tgenerator = generator.with_rate_limiter(MinIntervalRateLimiter.from_rpm(60, max_concurrent=5))\n109\t```\n110\t\n111\t## Custom middleware\n112\t\n113\tFor advanced cross-cutting concerns (logging, caching, etc.), you can write custom middleware by subclassing `CompletionMiddleware` and adding it to the `middlewares` list:\n114\t\n115\t```python\n116\timport logging\n117\tfrom typing import Any\n118\t\n119\tfrom giskard.agents import Message\n120\tfrom giskard.agents.generators import GenerationParams, Response\n121\tfrom giskard.agents.generators.middleware import CompletionMiddleware, NextFn\n122\t\n123\t@CompletionMiddleware.register(\"logging\")\n124\tclass LoggingMiddleware(CompletionMiddleware):\n125\t    async def call(\n126\t        self,\n127\t        messages: list[Message],\n128\t        params: GenerationParams | None,\n129\t        metadata: dict[str, Any] | None,\n130\t        next_fn: NextFn,\n131\t    ) -> Response:\n132\t        logging.info(f\"Sending {len(messages)} messages\")\n133\t        response = await next_fn(messages, params, metadata)\n134\t        logging.info(f\"Got response: {response.finish_reason}\")\n135\t        return response\n136\t\n137\tgenerator = agents.Generator(\n138\t    model=\"openai/gpt-4o-mini\",\n139\t    middlewares=[LoggingMiddleware()],\n140\t)\n141\t```\n142\t\n143\tCustom middlewares run after the built-in retry and rate-limiter middleware.\n144\t\n145\t## Structured output\n146\t\n147\tYou can specify the output model for the workflow, and this will be passed to\n148\teach completion call:\n149\t\n150\t```python\n151\tfrom pydantic import BaseModel\n152\t\n153\tclass SimpleOutput(BaseModel):\n154\t    mood: str\n155\t    greeting: str\n156\t\n157\tchat = await (\n158\t    generator.chat(\"Hello!\")\n159\t    .with_output(SimpleOutput)\n160\t    .run()\n161\t)\n162\t\n163\tassert isinstance(chat.output, SimpleOutput)\n164\tassert chat.output.mood == \"happy\"\n165\t```\n166\t\n167\t## Inputs and templates\n168\t\n169\t### Inline templates\n170\t\n171\tYou can associate input variables to a workflow, and use them in the messages thanks to jinja2 templating. By default, strings passed to `chat()` are literal text; pass `as_template=True` when the string should be rendered as Jinja2.\n172\t\n173\tHere's an example:\n174\t\n175\t```python\n176\t# This will run a chat with the message \"Hello Test Bot, how are you?\"\n177\tchat = await (\n178\t    generator.chat(\n179\t        \"Hello {{ name_of_the_bot }}, how are you?\", as_template=True\n180\t    )\n181\t    .with_inputs(name_of_the_bot=\"Test Bot\")\n182\t    .run()\n183\t)\n184\t```\n185\t\n186\t### External templates\n187\t\n188\tFor more complicated prompts you can define your template in a separate file. First tell `giskard.agents` where to find the templates (you probably want to do this in your `__init__.py` file):\n189\t\n190\t```python\n191\tagents.set_prompts_path(\"path/to/the/prompts\")\n192\t```\n193\t\n194\tWrite your templates in jinja2:\n195\t\n196\t```jinja\n197\tHello {{ name_of_the_bot }}, how are you?\n198\t```\n199\t\n200\t```python\n201\tchat = await (\n202\t    generator.template(\"hello_template.j2\")\n203\t    .with_inputs(name_of_the_bot=\"Test Bot\")\n204\t    .run()\n205\t)\n206\t```\n207\t\n208\t### Multi-message templates\n209\t\n210\tSometimes you may want to use more complex, multi-message prompts. This is particularly useful when you need a few-shots chat that includes examples.\n211\tFor this need, `giskard.agents` provides a special syntax to define multi-message prompts.\n212\t\n213\t```jinja\n214\t{% message system %}\n215\tYou are an impartial evaluator of scientific theories. Your only job is to rate them on a scale of 1-5, where:\n216\t1 = \"This theory belongs in the same category as 'the Earth is flat'\"\n217\t2 = \"More holes than Swiss cheese, but at least it's creative\"\n218\t3 = \"Could be true, could be false, Schrödinger's theory\"\n219\t4 = \"Almost as solid as the theory of gravity\"\n220\t5 = \"This theory is so good, even the experimentalists are convinced!\"\n221\t\n222\tThe user will provide you with a scientific theory to evaluate. Respond with ONLY a number from 1-5.\n223\t{% endmessage %}\n224\t\n225\t{# Example #}\n226\t{% message user %}\n227\tThe universe is actually a giant simulation running on a quantum computer in a higher dimension, and we're all just NPCs in someone's cosmic video game.\n228\t{% endmessage %}\n229\t\n230\t{% message assistant %}\n231\t3\n232\t{% endmessage %}\n233\t\n234\t{# Actual input #}\n235\t{% message user %}\n236\t{{ theory }}\n237\t{% endmessage %}\n238\t```\n239\t\n240\tYou can then load the template as usual:\n241\t\n242\t```python\n243\tchat = await (\n244\t    generator.template(\"evaluators.scientific_theory\")\n245\t    .with_inputs(theory=\"Normandy is actually the center of the universe because its perfect balance of rain, cheese, and cider creates a quantum field that bends space-time, making it the most harmonious place on Earth.\")\n246\t    .run()\n247\t)\n248\t\n249\tscore = int(chat.last.content)\n250\tassert score == 5\n251\t```\n252\t\n253\t## Input batches\n254\t\n255\tYou can run multiple chats with different inputs by passing a list of inputs to the `run_batch` method.\n256\t\n257\t```python\n258\tchats = await (\n259\t    generator.chat(\"What's the weather in {{ city }}?\", as_template=True)\n260\t    .run_batch([{\"city\": \"Paris\"}, {\"city\": \"London\"}])\n261\t)\n262\tassert len(chats) == 2\n263\t```\n264\t\n265\t## Tools\n266\t\n267\tYou can define tools using the `@agents.tool` decorator. Tools will be automatically called when the workflow is run.\n268\t\n269\tWhen defining tools, you need to make sure that all tool arguments have type hints. These will be used to define the tool schema. You must also provide a docstring, which will be used to describe the tool to the LLM. If you include the parameters in the docstring, their descriptions will be automatically added to the tool schema.\n270\t\n271\tThis can be combined with all functionalities described earlier. Here's an example:\n272\t\n273\t```python\n274\tfrom giskard import agents\n275\t\n276\t@agents.tool\n277\tdef get_weather(city: str) -> str:\n278\t    \"\"\"Get the weather in a city.\n279\t\n280\t    Parameters\n281\t    ----------\n282\t    city: str\n283\t        The city to get the weather for.\n284\t    \"\"\"\n285\t    if city == \"Paris\":\n286\t        return f\"It's raining in {city}.\"\n287\t\n288\t    return f\"It's sunny in {city}.\"\n289\t\n290\t# Run parallel chats with tools\n291\tchats = await (\n292\t    generator.chat(\"Hello, what's the weather in {{ city }}?\", as_template=True)\n293\t    .with_tools(get_weather)\n294\t    .run_batch([{\"city\": \"Paris\"}, {\"city\": \"London\"}])\n295\t)\n296\t\n297\tassert \"rain\" in chats[0].last.content\n298\tassert \"sun\" in chats[1].last.content\n299\t```\n300\t\n301\t### Run context\n302\t\n303\tTools can access a `RunContext` object that acts as a storage memory for the run. This can be useful to store information that is needed for the next tool calls.\n304\t\n305\tThe `RunContext` object will be automatically passed to the tool if you specify the type hint.\n306\t\n307\t```python\n308\t@agents.tool\n309\tdef get_weather(city: str, run_context: agents.RunContext) -> str:\n310\t    previously_asked_cities = run_context.get(\"previously_asked_cities\", [])\n311\t\n312\t    if city in previously_asked_cities:\n313\t        return f\"I've already asked this!\"\n314\t\n315\t    run_context.set(\"previously_asked_cities\", previously_asked_cities + [city])\n316\t    return f\"It's raining in {city}.\"\n317\t```\n318\t\n319\tThe run context will be shared between all tool calls in the same run.\n320\t\n321\tYou can also retrieve it after the run is complete:\n322\t\n323\t```python\n324\tchat = await (\n325\t    generator.chat(\"Hello, what's the weather in {{ city }}?\", as_template=True)\n326\t    .with_tools(get_weather)\n327\t    .with_inputs(city=\"Paris\")\n328\t    .run()\n329\t)\n330\t\n331\tassert \"Paris\" in chat.context.get(\"previously_asked_cities\")\n332\t```\n333\t\n334\tTo initialize the run context, you can pass it to the workflow with the `with_context` method:\n335\t\n336\t```python\n337\trun_context = agents.RunContext()\n338\trun_context.set(\"previously_asked_cities\", [\"Paris\"])\n339\t\n340\tchat = await (\n341\t    generator.chat(\"Hello, what's the weather in {{ city }}?\", as_template=True)\n342\t    .with_context(run_context)\n343\t    .with_tools(get_weather)\n344\t    .run()\n345\t)\n346\t```\n347\t\n348\t## Error handling\n349\t\n350\t### Errors during workflow execution\n351\t\n352\tYou can specify the error handling policy for the workflow. By default, the workflow will raise an error if an error occurs. You can change this behavior by passing the `on_error` method.\n353\t\n354\tYou can choose to:\n355\t\n356\t- Raise an error (`ErrorPolicy.RAISE`)\n357\t- Return the chat with the error (`ErrorPolicy.RETURN`). The chat will have a `failed` attribute set to `True`, and an `error` attribute with a serializable error message.\n358\t- For multi-run methods (e.g. `run_many` or `run_batch`), you can discard the failed chats (`ErrorPolicy.SKIP`). You will then only get the successful chats (potentially an empty list).\n359\t\n360\tNote: when running a single chat (`workflow.run(...)`), error policy `SKIP` behaves as `RETURN`, returning a `Chat` object with the error.\n361\t\n362\t```python\n363\tfrom giskard.agents import ErrorPolicy\n364\t\n365\t# This may return fewer than 3 chats if some fail.\n366\tchats = await generator.chat(\"Hello!\", role=\"user\").on_error(ErrorPolicy.SKIP).run_many(n=3)\n367\t\n368\t# This will return 3 chats, some may be in failed state.\n369\tchats = await generator.chat(\"Hello!\", role=\"user\").on_error(ErrorPolicy.RETURN).run_many(n=3)\n370\t\n371\tfor chat in chats:\n372\t    if chat.failed:\n373\t        print(\"CHAT FAILED:\", chat.error.message)\n374\t```\n375\t\n376\t### Errors during tool calls\n377\t\n378\tBy default, `giskard.agents` will catch errors during tool calls and return the error message as a tool result. This will let the agent decide what to do with the error (whether retrying or moving on).\n379\tYou can change this behavior by passing the `catch=None` on the tool decorator. In this case, the error will be raised and passed to the workflow, which will then handle it according to the workflow error handling policy.\n380\t\n381\t```python\n382\t# Default behavior, will catch errors\n383\t@agents.tool\n384\tdef get_weather(city: str) -> str:\n385\t    raise ValueError(\"City not found\")\n386\t\n387\tresult = await get_weather.run(arguments={\"city\": \"Paris\"})\n388\tprint(result) # \"ERROR: City not found\"\n389\t\n390\t\n391\t# Opt out of the catch\n392\t@agents.tool(catch=None)\n393\tdef get_weather(city: str) -> str:\n394\t    raise ValueError(\"City not found\")\n395\t\n396\t# This will raise an exception\n397\tresult = await get_weather.run(arguments={\"city\": \"Paris\"})\n398\t```\n399\t\n400\t## Development\n401\t\n402\t### Quick Setup\n403\t\n404\tFor quick development setup, use the provided Makefile:\n405\t\n406\t```bash\n407\tmake setup  # Install deps + tools\n408\tmake help   # See all available commands\n409\t```\n410\t\n411\t### Manual Setup\n412\t\n413\tInstall the project dependencies:\n414\t\n415\t```bash\n416\tuv sync\n417\t```\n418\t\n419\tInstall development tools:\n420\t\n421\t```bash\n422\tuv tool install ruff\n423\tuv tool install vermin\n424\tuv tool install pre-commit --with pre-commit-uv\n425\t```\n426\t\n427\tNote: `pytest` and `pip-audit` are included in dev dependencies since they need access to the project code.\n428\t\n429\t### Common Tasks\n430\t\n431\t```bash\n432\tmake test          # Run tests\n433\tmake lint          # Run linting\n434\tmake format        # Format code\n435\tmake check-format  # Check if code is formatted\n436\tmake check         # Run all checks (lint + format + compatibility + security)\n437\tmake ci            # Simulate CI locally\n438\tmake clean         # Clean build artifacts\n439\t```\n440\t\n441\t### Python Compatibility\n442\t\n443\tThis project maintains compatibility with Python 3.12+. We use [vermin](https://github.com/netromdk/vermin) to ensure code compatibility:\n444\t\n445\t```bash\n446\t# Check Python 3.12 compatibility\n447\tmake check-compat\n448\t# or manually:\n449\tuv tool run vermin --target=3.12- --no-tips --violations .\n450\t```\n451\t\n452\t#### Setting up Pre-commit Hooks\n453\t\n454\tTo automatically check compatibility on every commit:\n455\t\n456\t```bash\n457\t# Quick setup (if you ran `make setup` this is already done)\n458\tmake pre-commit-install\n459\t\n460\t# Or manually:\n461\tuv tool install pre-commit --with pre-commit-uv\n462\tpre-commit install\n463\t\n464\t# Run on all files\n465\tmake pre-commit-run\n466\t```\n467\t\n468\tThe hooks will now run automatically on `git commit` and prevent commits that don't meet Python 3.12 compatibility requirements.\n469\t\n470\t### Security\n471\t\n472\tWe use [pip-audit](https://pypi.org/project/pip-audit/) to scan for known security vulnerabilities in dependencies:\n473\t\n474\t```bash\n475\t# Check for security vulnerabilities\n476\tmake security\n477\t# or manually:\n478\tuv run pip-audit\n479\t```\n480\t\n481\tBoth compatibility and security checks are automatically run in CI for every pull request.\n482\t\n483\t## License\n484\t\n485\tThis project is licensed under the MIT License - see the [LICENSE](LICENSE) file for details.\n486\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"cecb49f1-a503-4314-99a9-a51144ba81d8","uuid":"8baaa4f2-e0c0-47fc-bc67-d8d4eb7c3ff0","timestamp":"2026-04-06T17:30:41.795Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/libs/giskard-agents/README.md","content":"# Giskard Agents\n\nGiskard Agents is a lightweight library that orchestrates LLM completions and agents in parallel workflows. It enables multiple AI workflows to run independently while maintaining coordination and synchronization between them.\n\n## Requirements\n\n- Python 3.12 or higher\n\n## Installation\n\n### Using uv (recommended)\n\nInstall the package:\n\n```bash\nuv add giskard-agents\n```\n\nFor development, install with dev dependencies:\n\n```bash\nuv add giskard-agents --dev\n```\n\n## Core Concepts\n\nThree basic elements to keep in mind:\n\n- `Generator` corresponds to a conversational text generator. It represents a model with certain params and can run completions.\n- `ChatWorkflow` defines everything needed to run a chat with the generator. It handles templates, parsing, and tools.\n- `Chat` is the result of a pipeline run. It contains the generated messages and metadata.\n\nThe API is async throughout — all run methods return coroutines.\n\n## Basic usage\n\n### Running a chat\n\n```python\nfrom giskard import agents\n\ngenerator = agents.Generator(model=\"openai/gpt-4o-mini\")\n\n# generator.chat automatically creates a workflow that can be run.\nchat = await generator.chat(\"Hello, how are you?\").run()\n\n# print the content of the last message (in this case, the assistant's response)\nprint(chat.last.content)\n```\n\nYou can run multiple chats in parallel:\n\n```python\nchats = await generator.chat(\"Hello, how are you?\").run_many(n=3)\n```\n\nOr add multiple messages to the workflow:\n\n```python\n# The chat message role is \"user\" by default.\nchat = await (\n    generator\n    .chat(\"You are a helpful assistant.\", role=\"system\")\n    .chat(\"Hello, how are you?\")\n    .chat(\"I'm fine, thank you!\", role=\"assistant\")\n    .chat(\"What's your name?\")\n    .run()\n)\n```\n\n## Retries and rate limiting\n\nGenerators have built-in support for retries and rate limiting via dedicated fields. The correct middleware ordering is handled automatically (retry wraps rate limiting wraps custom middlewares).\n\n### Retries\n\nBy default, `LiteLLMGenerator` retries failed requests with exponential backoff using LiteLLM's retry-eligibility logic. You can customize the retry policy:\n\n```python\nfrom giskard.agents.generators.middleware import RetryPolicy\n\ngenerator = agents.Generator(\n    model=\"openai/gpt-4o-mini\",\n    retry_policy=RetryPolicy(max_attempts=5, base_delay=2.0, max_delay=30.0),\n)\n```\n\nOr use the convenience method:\n\n```python\ngenerator = agents.Generator(model=\"openai/gpt-4o-mini\").with_retries(5, base_delay=2.0, max_delay=30.0)\n```\n\n### Rate limiting\n\n```python\nfrom giskard.core import MinIntervalRateLimiter\n\ngenerator = agents.Generator(\n    model=\"openai/gpt-4o-mini\",\n    rate_limiter=MinIntervalRateLimiter.from_rpm(60, max_concurrent=5),\n)\n```\n\nOr use the convenience method:\n\n```python\ngenerator = generator.with_rate_limiter(MinIntervalRateLimiter.from_rpm(60, max_concurrent=5))\n```\n\n## Custom middleware\n\nFor advanced cross-cutting concerns (logging, caching, etc.), you can write custom middleware by subclassing `CompletionMiddleware` and adding it to the `middlewares` list:\n\n```python\nimport logging\nfrom typing import Any\n\nfrom giskard.agents import Message\nfrom giskard.agents.generators import GenerationParams, Response\nfrom giskard.agents.generators.middleware import CompletionMiddleware, NextFn\n\n@CompletionMiddleware.register(\"logging\")\nclass LoggingMiddleware(CompletionMiddleware):\n    async def call(\n        self,\n        messages: list[Message],\n        params: GenerationParams | None,\n        metadata: dict[str, Any] | None,\n        next_fn: NextFn,\n    ) -> Response:\n        logging.info(f\"Sending {len(messages)} messages\")\n        response = await next_fn(messages, params, metadata)\n        logging.info(f\"Got response: {response.finish_reason}\")\n        return response\n\ngenerator = agents.Generator(\n    model=\"openai/gpt-4o-mini\",\n    middlewares=[LoggingMiddleware()],\n)\n```\n\nCustom middlewares run after the built-in retry and rate-limiter middleware.\n\n## Structured output\n\nYou can specify the output model for the workflow, and this will be passed to\neach completion call:\n\n```python\nfrom pydantic import BaseModel\n\nclass SimpleOutput(BaseModel):\n    mood: str\n    greeting: str\n\nchat = await (\n    generator.chat(\"Hello!\")\n    .with_output(SimpleOutput)\n    .run()\n)\n\nassert isinstance(chat.output, SimpleOutput)\nassert chat.output.mood == \"happy\"\n```\n\n## Inputs and templates\n\n### Inline templates\n\nYou can associate input variables to a workflow, and use them in the messages thanks to jinja2 templating. By default, strings passed to `chat()` are literal text; pass `as_template=True` when the string should be rendered as Jinja2.\n\nHere's an example:\n\n```python\n# This will run a chat with the message \"Hello Test Bot, how are you?\"\nchat = await (\n    generator.chat(\n        \"Hello {{ name_of_the_bot }}, how are you?\", as_template=True\n    )\n    .with_inputs(name_of_the_bot=\"Test Bot\")\n    .run()\n)\n```\n\n### External templates\n\nFor more complicated prompts you can define your template in a separate file. First tell `giskard.agents` where to find the templates (you probably want to do this in your `__init__.py` file):\n\n```python\nagents.set_prompts_path(\"path/to/the/prompts\")\n```\n\nWrite your templates in jinja2:\n\n```jinja\nHello {{ name_of_the_bot }}, how are you?\n```\n\n```python\nchat = await (\n    generator.template(\"hello_template.j2\")\n    .with_inputs(name_of_the_bot=\"Test Bot\")\n    .run()\n)\n```\n\n### Multi-message templates\n\nSometimes you may want to use more complex, multi-message prompts. This is particularly useful when you need a few-shots chat that includes examples.\nFor this need, `giskard.agents` provides a special syntax to define multi-message prompts.\n\n```jinja\n{% message system %}\nYou are an impartial evaluator of scientific theories. Your only job is to rate them on a scale of 1-5, where:\n1 = \"This theory belongs in the same category as 'the Earth is flat'\"\n2 = \"More holes than Swiss cheese, but at least it's creative\"\n3 = \"Could be true, could be false, Schrödinger's theory\"\n4 = \"Almost as solid as the theory of gravity\"\n5 = \"This theory is so good, even the experimentalists are convinced!\"\n\nThe user will provide you with a scientific theory to evaluate. Respond with ONLY a number from 1-5.\n{% endmessage %}\n\n{# Example #}\n{% message user %}\nThe universe is actually a giant simulation running on a quantum computer in a higher dimension, and we're all just NPCs in someone's cosmic video game.\n{% endmessage %}\n\n{% message assistant %}\n3\n{% endmessage %}\n\n{# Actual input #}\n{% message user %}\n{{ theory }}\n{% endmessage %}\n```\n\nYou can then load the template as usual:\n\n```python\nchat = await (\n    generator.template(\"evaluators.scientific_theory\")\n    .with_inputs(theory=\"Normandy is actually the center of the universe because its perfect balance of rain, cheese, and cider creates a quantum field that bends space-time, making it the most harmonious place on Earth.\")\n    .run()\n)\n\nscore = int(chat.last.content)\nassert score == 5\n```\n\n## Input batches\n\nYou can run multiple chats with different inputs by passing a list of inputs to the `run_batch` method.\n\n```python\nchats = await (\n    generator.chat(\"What's the weather in {{ city }}?\", as_template=True)\n    .run_batch([{\"city\": \"Paris\"}, {\"city\": \"London\"}])\n)\nassert len(chats) == 2\n```\n\n## Tools\n\nYou can define tools using the `@agents.tool` decorator. Tools will be automatically called when the workflow is run.\n\nWhen defining tools, you need to make sure that all tool arguments have type hints. These will be used to define the tool schema. You must also provide a docstring, which will be used to describe the tool to the LLM. If you include the parameters in the docstring, their descriptions will be automatically added to the tool schema.\n\nThis can be combined with all functionalities described earlier. Here's an example:\n\n```python\nfrom giskard import agents\n\n@agents.tool\ndef get_weather(city: str) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Get the weather in a city.\n\n    Parameters\n    ----------\n    city: str\n        The city to get the weather for.\n    \"\"\"\n    if city == \"Paris\":\n        return f\"It's raining in {city}.\"\n\n    return f\"It's sunny in {city}.\"\n\n# Run parallel chats with tools\nchats = await (\n    generator.chat(\"Hello, what's the weather in {{ city }}?\", as_template=True)\n    .with_tools(get_weather)\n    .run_batch([{\"city\": \"Paris\"}, {\"city\": \"London\"}])\n)\n\nassert \"rain\" in chats[0].last.content\nassert \"sun\" in chats[1].last.content\n```\n\n### Run context\n\nTools can access a `RunContext` object that acts as a storage memory for the run. This can be useful to store information that is needed for the next tool calls.\n\nThe `RunContext` object will be automatically passed to the tool if you specify the type hint.\n\n```python\n@agents.tool\ndef get_weather(city: str, run_context: agents.RunContext) -> str:\n    previously_asked_cities = run_context.get(\"previously_asked_cities\", [])\n\n    if city in previously_asked_cities:\n        return f\"I've already asked this!\"\n\n    run_context.set(\"previously_asked_cities\", previously_asked_cities + [city])\n    return f\"It's raining in {city}.\"\n```\n\nThe run context will be shared between all tool calls in the same run.\n\nYou can also retrieve it after the run is complete:\n\n```python\nchat = await (\n    generator.chat(\"Hello, what's the weather in {{ city }}?\", as_template=True)\n    .with_tools(get_weather)\n    .with_inputs(city=\"Paris\")\n    .run()\n)\n\nassert \"Paris\" in chat.context.get(\"previously_asked_cities\")\n```\n\nTo initialize the run context, you can pass it to the workflow with the `with_context` method:\n\n```python\nrun_context = agents.RunContext()\nrun_context.set(\"previously_asked_cities\", [\"Paris\"])\n\nchat = await (\n    generator.chat(\"Hello, what's the weather in {{ city }}?\", as_template=True)\n    .with_context(run_context)\n    .with_tools(get_weather)\n    .run()\n)\n```\n\n## Error handling\n\n### Errors during workflow execution\n\nYou can specify the error handling policy for the workflow. By default, the workflow will raise an error if an error occurs. You can change this behavior by passing the `on_error` method.\n\nYou can choose to:\n\n- Raise an error (`ErrorPolicy.RAISE`)\n- Return the chat with the error (`ErrorPolicy.RETURN`). The chat will have a `failed` attribute set to `True`, and an `error` attribute with a serializable error message.\n- For multi-run methods (e.g. `run_many` or `run_batch`), you can discard the failed chats (`ErrorPolicy.SKIP`). You will then only get the successful chats (potentially an empty list).\n\nNote: when running a single chat (`workflow.run(...)`), error policy `SKIP` behaves as `RETURN`, returning a `Chat` object with the error.\n\n```python\nfrom giskard.agents import ErrorPolicy\n\n# This may return fewer than 3 chats if some fail.\nchats = await generator.chat(\"Hello!\", role=\"user\").on_error(ErrorPolicy.SKIP).run_many(n=3)\n\n# This will return 3 chats, some may be in failed state.\nchats = await generator.chat(\"Hello!\", role=\"user\").on_error(ErrorPolicy.RETURN).run_many(n=3)\n\nfor chat in chats:\n    if chat.failed:\n        print(\"CHAT FAILED:\", chat.error.message)\n```\n\n### Errors during tool calls\n\nBy default, `giskard.agents` will catch errors during tool calls and return the error message as a tool result. This will let the agent decide what to do with the error (whether retrying or moving on).\nYou can change this behavior by passing the `catch=None` on the tool decorator. In this case, the error will be raised and passed to the workflow, which will then handle it according to the workflow error handling policy.\n\n```python\n# Default behavior, will catch errors\n@agents.tool\ndef get_weather(city: str) -> str:\n    raise ValueError(\"City not found\")\n\nresult = await get_weather.run(arguments={\"city\": \"Paris\"})\nprint(result) # \"ERROR: City not found\"\n\n\n# Opt out of the catch\n@agents.tool(catch=None)\ndef get_weather(city: str) -> str:\n    raise ValueError(\"City not found\")\n\n# This will raise an exception\nresult = await get_weather.run(arguments={\"city\": \"Paris\"})\n```\n\n## Development\n\n### Quick Setup\n\nFor quick development setup, use the provided Makefile:\n\n```bash\nmake setup  # Install deps + tools\nmake help   # See all available commands\n```\n\n### Manual Setup\n\nInstall the project dependencies:\n\n```bash\nuv sync\n```\n\nInstall development tools:\n\n```bash\nuv tool install ruff\nuv tool install vermin\nuv tool install pre-commit --with pre-commit-uv\n```\n\nNote: `pytest` and `pip-audit` are included in dev dependencies since they need access to the project code.\n\n### Common Tasks\n\n```bash\nmake test          # Run tests\nmake lint          # Run linting\nmake format        # Format code\nmake check-format  # Check if code is formatted\nmake check         # Run all checks (lint + format + compatibility + security)\nmake ci            # Simulate CI locally\nmake clean         # Clean build artifacts\n```\n\n### Python Compatibility\n\nThis project maintains compatibility with Python 3.12+. We use [vermin](https://github.com/netromdk/vermin) to ensure code compatibility:\n\n```bash\n# Check Python 3.12 compatibility\nmake check-compat\n# or manually:\nuv tool run vermin --target=3.12- --no-tips --violations .\n```\n\n#### Setting up Pre-commit Hooks\n\nTo automatically check compatibility on every commit:\n\n```bash\n# Quick setup (if you ran `make setup` this is already done)\nmake pre-commit-install\n\n# Or manually:\nuv tool install pre-commit --with pre-commit-uv\npre-commit install\n\n# Run on all files\nmake pre-commit-run\n```\n\nThe hooks will now run automatically on `git commit` and prevent commits that don't meet Python 3.12 compatibility requirements.\n\n### Security\n\nWe use [pip-audit](https://pypi.org/project/pip-audit/) to scan for known security vulnerabilities in dependencies:\n\n```bash\n# Check for security vulnerabilities\nmake security\n# or manually:\nuv run pip-audit\n```\n\nBoth compatibility and security checks are automatically run in CI for every pull request.\n\n## License\n\nThis project is licensed under the MIT License - see the [LICENSE](LICENSE) file for details.\n","numLines":486,"startLine":1,"totalLines":486}}}
